post_text:
NKY Health would like to show the world how NKY works together to slow the spread of COVID-19, and we need your help. Email photos of you and your loved ones wearing face coverings, social distancing or hand washing to doingitright@nkyhealth.org to be featured on NKY Health's social media pages*. Let’s show everyone how we’re #DoingItRightNKY!
*By submitting photos, you give consent to be identified on social media. Identifying information may specifically include my name and/or city of residence. Information given to the Health Department may be published or distributed for the purpose of education and promotion of Health Department programs and services (i.e. article, billboard, advertisement, report, conference session, social media post or educational flyer).

This drive-through testing will be held on the days/locations listed below.
When: Monday through Friday (beginning August 6)
8 a.m. to 2:30 p.m.

Where: Erlanger
Atlantic Corporate Center
25 Atlantic Avenue
Erlanger, KY 41018

When: Tuesdays and Thursdays (beginning August 11)
5 p.m. – 9 p.m.

Where: Alexandria
St. Elizabeth Alexandria Imaging Location
7200 Alexandria Pike
Alexandria, KY 41001

Symptomatic or asymptomatic Kentucky residents should schedule an appointment online at bit.ly/3fwxlNS.

post_text: An investigation in Missouri found no clients were known to be infected with COVID-19 after 139 clients were exposed to two hairstylists with the disease. The hairstylists and clients wore face coverings, which likely helped prevent the spread of COVID-19. Wear a cloth face covering consistently and correctly in public and around people not living in your household to prevent the spread of COVID-19.

shared_text:
Kenton County - Government
July 10 at 4:59 PM ·

Governor Beshear announced a drive-thru testing site for COVID-19 in Kenton County that will be active Tuesday-Thursday throughout the rest of July. The site will begin testing on Tuesday, July 14th and will complete on Thursday, July 30th.

To learn more and to make an appointment, visit: https://www.thelittleclinic.com/drivethru-testing. You can also call (888) 852-2567 (select option 1, then option 3).

Testing is possible through a partnership with the Governor’s Office, Kroger Health, UPS, Gravity Diagnostics, Kentucky Division of Emergency Management, Kentucky Department for Public Health, Kentucky State Police, Kentucky Transportation Cabinet, Kentucky National Guard and Kenton County.

post_text: As plans for reopening businesses are created, it is important that business owners and employers start thinking now about the policies and procedures they will need to put into place to ensure a safe and healthy workforce. One such action is to flush the water in your building’s pipes prior to reopening. When a building is closed for an extended period of time, the water in the building’s pipes become stagnant. Stagnant water in the pipes may lead to health concerns including the growth of bacteria such as Legionella. For more information, visit https://bit.ly/2YjePn8 #healthyatwork
text: As plans for reopening businesses are created, it is important that business owners and employers start thinking now about the policies and procedures they will need to put into place to ensure a safe and healthy workforce. One such action is to flush the water in your building’s pipes prior to reopening. When a building is closed for an extended period of time, the water in the building’s pipes become stagnant. Stagnant water in the pipes may lead to health concerns including the growth of bacteria such as Legionella. For more information, visit https://bit.ly/2YjePn8 #healthyatwork

post_text:
There is a lot of misinformation about the differences between the flu and COVID-19. Here are some key facts:

- There is significant knowledge regarding the flu, its patterns, and treatment. COVID-19 is still very unpredictable and health experts are still learning. We’ve never experienced COVID-19 before.
- The flu has a vaccine while COVID-19 does not.
- The COVID-19 situation is changing rapidly. Since this disease is caused by a new virus, people do not have immunity to it, and a vaccine may be many months away. Doctors and scientists are working on estimating the mortality rate of COVID-19, but at present, it is thought to be higher than that of most strains of the flu.

It’s important for us to continue practicing social distancing and maintaining the CDC’s recommendations for protecting ourselves and others. #healthyathome #COVID19facts

post_text:
Interactive map finds free meals during school closures
WASHINGTON, April 3, 2020 –The U.S. Department of Agriculture (USDA) today announced the launch of an online tool – the “Meals for Kids” Site Finder – to help families find meals for children while schools are closed during the coronavirus pandemic. This is the latest in a series of swift actions USDA has taken to keep children and low-income individuals fed during the ongoing health crisis.

The “Meals for Kids” interactive map directs people to local sites where kids can get free meals. The site finder currently lists more than 20,000 meal sites from 23 states, and more sites will be added as states submit data each week. The map is available in both English and Spanish at www.fns.usda.gov/meals4kids.

post_text:
NKY Health will resume syringe access exchange program services starting Tuesday, March 31. We would like to thank
Caracole for allowing us to use their mobile unit in Campbell and Kenton Counties. Without their generosity, we would not be able to provide this important service to those communities.

County SAEP Schedules:

Campbell County Mobile SAEP – Every Tuesday from 1 – 4pm at St. Elizabeth Urgent Care in Newport

Grant County SAEP – Every Wednesday from 1 – 4pm at the Grant County Health Center

Kenton County Mobile SAEP – Every Thursday from 1 – 4pm at St. Elizabeth Hospital in Covington

Health Department nurses will provide sterile equipment in exchange for used equipment, as well as naloxone overdose reversal kits. For more information, please visit https://nkyhealth.org/individual-or-family/individual-health/addiction-response/syringe-access-exchange-program/

If you are experiencing symptoms associated with COVID-19 (fever, cough, difficulty breathing), please stay at home and contact your health care provider.

NKY WIC Participants:

Your local WIC office would like to clear the air about false information that has appeared on social media sites. Your WIC benefits will not expire early. Keep your current eWIC card. Your current eWIC card will be used for future months' WIC food benefits.

We are currently seeing clients in clinic for WIC certifications and are trying to do WIC follow-ups by phone. If you have questions, call your WIC clinic. If you or a family member are sick, please do not come to the clinic, but give us a call so we can keep your WIC benefits going. We are also putting new WIC clients on the program.

Thank you,
NKY Health

post_text:
How to Help Children Dealing with Anxiety About COVID-19:

- Take care of yourself first.
- Provide an open, calm and reassuring environment.
- Make sure children feel comfortable enough to ask questions. Answer calmly, and model behaviors to them to stay safe - hand washing, hygiene, etc.
- Provide quality information. Don't mislead or lie to children.
- Provide routines for children.
- Limit children's social media time.
- If they don't want to talk about COVID-19 or how they're feeling, don't force them.
- While maintaining social distance, have children interact electronically with friends.

post_text:
Tips for Dealing with Anxiety About COVID-19:

- Stay informed with reliable sources, but don't overwhelm yourself - limit yourself on how much news you read/hear.
- Take a break from social media about COVID-19, especially the rumors and misinformation.
- Try to keep routines in your lives as much as possible.
- Take care of yourself, and stay healthy. Take your medication, eat a healthy diet and exercise. Outdoor activities are great now that spring is almost here. Make sure you are getting enough sleep.
- Find ways to relieve your stress. Take up a new hobby, and find enjoyable activities to help you relax.
- Maintain social distancing, but at the same time maintain social connectedness. Connect virtually with friends and families.

Adults over the age of 60 and people who have severe chronic medical conditions like heart disease, lung disease, kidney disease or diabetes seem to be at higher risk for more serious COVID-19 illness. If you are at higher risk, the following is recommended:

- Make sure you have access to several weeks of medications and supplies in case you need to stay home for prolonged periods of time.
- When you go out in public, keep away from others who are sick, limit close contact and wash your hands often.
- Avoid crowds. Do not fly or take cruises.

For more information, visit www.kycovid19.ky.gov or call 1-800-722-5725.

At this time, there are no reported cases of the 2019 novel coronavirus (COVID-19) in Kentucky, but here are steps you can take everyday to prevent the spread of germs:

- Avoid close contact with people who are sick, and stay home when you are sick.
- Cover your mouth and nose with a tissue when you cough or sneeze. Then, throw the tissue away.
- Wash your hands with soap and water.
- Clean and disinfect objects and surfaces that may be contaminated with germs.

post_text: Public Health Hero Award - NKY Health would like to recognize Kentucky Representative Kim Moser as a true Public Health Hero for her sponsorship of Kentucky House Bill 11, otherwise known as the Tobacco Free Schools Bill. This bill, which became law in 2019, has led to 100% of the public school districts in Northern Kentucky adopting smoke-free policies. Smoke-free policies in schools not only protect students and staff from the harmful effects of secondhand smoke, but also support healthy role modeling for youth.

post_text: Public Health Hero Award - NKY Health would like to recognize Ashel Kruetzkamp, MSN, RN and Leigh Tekulve, MSN, RN, St. Elizabeth Healthcare, for championing routine HIV and hepatitis C testing and hepatitis A vaccines to high-risk individuals who present to St. Elizabeth Emergency Departments. Early identification of diseases like HIV and hepatitis C can lead to earlier treatment, better health outcomes and reduce the spread of infection in the community. Ashel and Leigh are true Public Health Heroes.

post_text: Public Health Hero Award - NKY Health would like to recognize Bill Birkle and the Kentucky Fire Commission as true Public Health Heroes for the use of their mobile command center to support harm reduction services in Covington and Newport. As of Feb. 1, the Newport syringe access exchange program has served 805 individuals, and the Covington program has served 1,473 individuals. The syringe access exchange program creates a healthier community by preventing overdose deaths, reducing the spread of infectious diseases such as HIV and hepatitis C, and providing connections to addiction treatment and other services.

January 24 at 8:30 AM ·

Member of the Day: Northern Kentucky Health Department

January 24, 2020

The Northern Kentucky Health Department is the public agency charged with performing mandated public health services and addressing priority community health needs. A staff of approximately 150 employees serves Boone, Kenton, Campbell and Grant counties.

Our mission is to prevent disease, promote wellness and protect against health threats. Our vision is to be a valued leader and community partner, with the resources needed to effectively address public health challenges so Northern Kentucky is the healthiest region in the nation.
